05997nam a22008535i 9781400826285DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984643727  a97814008262857 a10.1515/97814008262852doi  a(DE-B1597)446431  a(OCoLC)979578333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aKF5130.T48 2004 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a347.73/1200aThat Eminent Tribunal :bJudicial Supremacy and the Constitution /ced. by Christopher Wolfe.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Forum Books ;v5200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Is the Constitution Whatever the Winners Say It Is? -- tChapter 2. Nationhood and Judicial Supremacy -- tChapter 3. “Casey at the Bat”—Taking Another Swing at Planned Parenthood v. Casey -- tChapter 4. Antijural Jurisprudence: The Vices of the Judges Enter a New Stage -- tChapter 5. Judicial Power and the Withering of Civil Society -- tChapter 6. The Academy, the Courts, and the Culture of Rationalism -- tChapter 7. Judicial Moral Expertise and Real-World Constraints on Judicial Moral Reasoning -- tChapter 8. Toward a More Balanced History of the Supreme Court -- tChapter 9. Judicial Review and Republican Government -- tChapter 10. The Casey Five versus the Federalism Five: Supreme Legislator or Prudent Umpire? -- tChapter 11. The Rehnquist Court and “Conservative Judicial Activism” -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe role of the United States Supreme Court has been deeply controversial throughout American history. Should the Court undertake the task of guarding a wide variety of controversial and often unenumerated rights? Or should it confine itself to enforcing specific constitutional provisions, leaving other issues (even those of rights) to the democratic process? That Eminent Tribunal brings together a distinguished group of legal scholars and political scientists who argue that the Court's power has exceeded its appropriate bounds, and that sound republican principles require greater limits on that power. They reach this conclusion by an interesting variety of paths, and despite varied political convictions. Some of the essays debate the explicit claims to constitutional authority laid out by the Supreme Court itself in Planned Parenthood v. Casey and similar cases, and others focus on the defenses of judicial authority found commonly in legal scholarship (e.g., the allegedly superior moral reasoning of judges, or judges' supposed track record of superior political decision making). The authors find these arguments wanting and contend that the principles of republicanism and the contemporary form of judicial review exercised by the Supreme Court are fundamentally incompatible. The contributors include Hadley Arkes, Gerard V. Bradley, George Liebmann, Michael McConnell, Robert F. Nagel, Jack Wade Nowlin, Steven D. Smith, Jeremy Waldron, Keith E. Whittington, Christopher Wolfe, and Michael P. Zuckert.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aArkes, Hadley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Gerard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiebmann, George W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcConnell, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagel, Robert F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNowlin, Jack Wade, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Steven D., e